{"timestamp": "2025-12-05 22:35:11.497686", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting diagnosis report\nTimestamp: now\n\n1) Summary / overall health\n- IP reachability across the network is generally healthy: ICMP pings between hosts, servers and the load-balancer succeed and FRR/OSPF appears to be advertising networks (hosts and servers are reachable by IP).\n- DNS and DHCP servers are present and reachable (DNS: 10.200.0.2, DHCP: 10.200.0.8).\n- The HTTP front-end (load_balancer, web99.local -> 10.200.0.7) is running (nginx is active and listening on :80).\n- However the backend web service tier is not healthy: Apache (httpd) on all backend web servers is inactive, and the load balancer configuration contains incorrect upstream IPs (typoed network). These two issues are the primary anomalies and appear to be the root causes of application-level failures.\n\n2) Abnormal behavior detected (high-level)\n- All backend web servers (web_server_0..web_server_3) show apache2.service state: inactive (dead).\n  Evidence:\n    - web_server_0: \"apache2.service ... Active: inactive (dead)\"\n    - web_server_1: same\n    - web_server_2: same\n    - web_server_3: same\n- The load balancer (nginx) upstream block contains upstream server IPs in the 20.200.0.0/24 network (20.200.0.2/3/4), while the actual server farm uses 10.200.0.0/24 addresses (web servers and DNS are at 10.200.0.x). This is a configuration error (likely a typo).\n  Evidence (nginx config excerpt):\n    upstream web99 {\n        server 20.200.0.2:80;\n        server 20.200.0.3:80;\n        server 20.200.0.4:80;\n    }\n  Actual addressing from reachability data:\n    - dns_server 10.200.0.2\n    - web_server_0 10.200.0.3\n    - web_server_1 10.200.0.4\n    - web_server_2 10.200.0.5\n    - web_server_3 10.200.0.6\n    - load_balancer 10.200.0.7\n- Attempts from the load_balancer to contact a backend HTTP endpoint return long timeouts (curl from load_balancer -> 10.200.0.3 resulted in 5.00s total with no starttransfer), consistent with the backends not answering TCP HTTP requests.\n  Evidence:\n    - curl from load_balancer to http://10.200.0.3: three runs, each total ≈ 5.00s with starttransfer 0.000000 — indicates the HTTP connection attempt did not complete and timed out.\n- From an example host (host_1_1_1_1) requesting http://10.200.0.7 (the load balancer) we get responses but with elevated start-transfer/total times (~0.27–0.44s start, ~1.03–1.24s total). That indicates the load balancer is responding to clients but there is latency/delay in delivering content (consistent with it struggling to reach healthy upstreams or returning an error page).\n  Evidence:\n    - curl timing from host_1_1_1_1 to http://10.200.0.7:\n      starttransfer: 0.266–0.438 s; total: 1.03–1.24 s (5 samples)\n\n3) Localization — which devices/components are implicated\n- load_balancer (10.200.0.7)\n  - nginx is active and listening on TCP/80 (nginx.service Active: active (running); netstat shows 0.0.0.0:80 LISTEN).\n  - nginx configuration upstream block references 20.200.0.x addresses (incorrect network).\n  - Evidence: systemctl status and netstat and nginx config excerpt returned from load_balancer.\n- web_server_0 .. web_server_3 (10.200.0.3–10.200.0.6)\n  - apache2.service is inactive on each web server (Active: inactive (dead)).\n  - Evidence: systemctl status output for each web server shows apache2 inactive.\n- dns_server, dhcp_server, and network routing infrastructure\n  - Appear functional for IP-level reachability (pings to hosts and servers succeed). No routing anomalies observed in the provided reachability matrix.\n\n4) Root cause analysis (most likely causes, supported by evidence)\n- Primary root cause 1: Backend application processes stopped\n  - All Apache services on the backend web servers are inactive. Even with correct load-balancer configuration, there are no HTTP servers listening on the expected backend hosts/ports. This explains inability of the load-balancer to contact working backends.\n  - Evidence: \"apache2.service ... Active: inactive (dead)\" on web_server_0..3.\n- Primary root cause 2: Load-balancer upstream misconfiguration (IP addressing error)\n  - The nginx upstream uses 20.200.0.x addresses which do not match the real backend IPs (10.200.0.x). This causes nginx to attempt to proxy to wrong/unroutable/unassigned addresses and fail.\n  - Evidence: nginx config upstream servers are 20.200.0.2/3/4, while actual web servers are 10.200.0.3/4/5/6 (dns_server is 10.200.0.2).\n- Combined effect / impact:\n  - Because of both issues, the load balancer cannot successfully proxy client requests to healthy application backends. The load-balancer is up and reachable, so clients see the front-end, but real application content will be unavailable or delayed (error pages/timeouts) because backends are unreachable or not serving HTTP.\n  - The presence of a wrong upstream network (20.200.0.x) may also cause nginx to attempt to reach nonexistent hosts and experience connection timeouts; even correcting the IP typo would leave the services down because apache is inactive — so both issues must be considered.\n\n5) Additional evidence gathered (selected outputs)\n- Reachability: ICMP pings between sample hosts and servers: successful (0% loss).\n  - Example: ping host_1_1_1_1 -> web_server_0: 4/4 packets, avg rtt ~2.945 ms.\n  - get_reachability results show many successful ping measurements across the fabric.\n- DNS resolution at client:\n  - getent hosts web99.local => \"10.200.0.7 web99.local\"\n  - ping web99.local from host_1_1_1_1 => 3/3 replies avg ~2.8 ms\n- load_balancer service and ports:\n  - systemctl status nginx => Active: active (running)\n  - netstat -tuln => 0.0.0.0:80 LISTEN\n- nginx config excerpt (from load_balancer):\n  - upstream web99 { server 20.200.0.2:80; server 20.200.0.3:80; server 20.200.0.4:80; }\n  - server block proxies to http://web99;\n- backend HTTP checks:\n  - systemctl status apache2 on web_server_0..3 => Active: inactive (dead)\n  - curl from load_balancer to http://10.200.0.3 => 3 attempts, each timed out at ~5.00s total (no starttransfer)\n\n6) Confidence and notes\n- Confidence: high that the two issues identified (nginx upstream address typo and apache services stopped) are the main root causes for application-level failure. The evidence directly shows misconfigured upstreams and inactive backend services.\n- Additional investigation that would further confirm / refine root cause:\n  - On web_server_0..3: check \"ss -lnt\" / \"netstat -ltn\" to confirm no process is listening on :80 and inspect apache logs (journalctl -u apache2 or /var/log/apache2/*) to see why apache stopped.\n  - On load_balancer: test curl to the misconfigured upstream IPs (20.200.0.2/3/4) to observe connectivity behavior; test curl to the correct backend IPs (10.200.0.3 etc.) to check whether TCP connection is refused or timed out.\n  - Check for any host firewall (iptables/nftables) on web servers that might be dropping TCP/80; confirm whether apache was intentionally stopped.\n  - Inspect nginx error logs to see proxy_pass failures and specific upstream error codes/timeouts.\n  - Verify any recent configuration changes or automation runs that could have caused apache to stop and/or introduced the upstream typo.\n\n7) Impact summary\n- Users can reach web99.local (load-balancer) but will experience errors, delays, or default/error pages because the load balancer cannot forward requests to functioning backend web servers.\n- Backend web servers are not serving HTTP (apache inactive), so even with correct upstream IPs, service would be down until the web servers’ HTTP service is restored.\n- DNS and IP routing appear OK; problem is at application and load-balancer configuration layer.\n\nEnd of diagnosis.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 33679, "output_tokens": 3721, "total_tokens": 37400, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 32512}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 1728}}}
